# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vidin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vidin/adrianople] Legends claim that Orestias was founded by Orestes, the son of Agamemnon and Clytemnestra.
[src:vidin/adrianople] Orestias or Orestia is thought to have been the same town as Uscudama (other variants: Uskudama, Uskadama, Uskodama) or Odrysa (other variants: Odrysia, Odrysos, Odrysus) which was the first Odrysian capital.
[src:vidin/adrianople] Orestias took its name by the Greeks, at least from the time Philip II of Macedon took over the town.
[src:vidin/adrianople] The Roman emperor Hadrian expanded the town into a city, gave it a strong fortification and renamed it to Hadrianopolis (Greek: Άδριανούπολις).
[src:vidin/adrianople] However the name Orestias was still used by many writers at the Byzantine era, along with Adrianoupolis.
[src:vidin/adrianople] It was the capital of the Byzantine theme of Macedonia.
[src:vidin/adrianople] During the Ottoman period the name of Adrianou(polis) was paraphrased by the Turks and eventually became Edirne.
[src:vidin/adrianople] In 1920 when the Greeks took over most of Eastern Thrace including Edirne, they restored the city's Roman name (Adrianoupolis) and not its old Greek name (Orestias), which was given to its suburb Karaağaç, in remembrance of the ancient Thracian town.
[src:vidin/adrianople] Orestiada (or Nea Orestias or New Orestias) is a modern Greek town founded in 1923 on a site 17 km (11 mi) to the south of Orestias, to house Greek refugees who had to abandon the latter border town, which was given to Turkey (along with two villages) by the Treaty of Lausanne.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The ***Alexiad*** (Attic Greek: Ἀλεξιάς, romanized: *Alexiás*) is a medieval historical and biographical text written around the year 1148, by the Byzantine princess Anna Komnene, daughter of Emperor Alexios I Komnenos.
[src:vidin/alexiad] It was written in a form of artificial Attic Greek, the literary dialect of classical Greece.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna described the political and military history of the Byzantine Empire during the reign of her father, thus providing a significant account on the Byzantium of the High Middle Ages.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Among other topics, the *Alexiad* documents the Byzantine Empire's interaction with the Crusades and highlights the conflicting perceptions of the East and West in the early 12th century.
[src:vidin/alexiad] It does not mention the schism of 1054 – a topic which is very common in contemporary writing.
[src:vidin/alexiad] It documents firsthand the decline of Byzantine cultural influence in eastern and western Europe, particularly in the West's increasing involvement in its geographic sphere.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The *Alexiad* was paraphrased in vernacular medieval Greek in the mid-14th century to increase its readability, which testifies to the work's lasting interest.
[src:vidin/alexiad] and the Crusaders Counsil, 13th century manuscript.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The book is divided into 15 books and a prologue.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Its scope is limited to the duration of Alexios' reign, which it is thus able to depict in full detail, especially regarding political relations between the Byzantine Empire and western European powers.
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses war against the Normans (1081–1082).
[src:vidin/alexiad] also addresses war against the Normans (1082–1083) and their first clash with the "heretics".
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses the end of war against the Normans (1085) and the death of Robert Guiscard.
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses war against the Scythians (1087–1090).
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses Turks, Franks, Cumans and Manicheans (1108–1115).
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses the end of the Scythian war (1091) and plots against the Emperor.
[src:vidin/alexiad] also addresses the First Crusade (1097–1104).
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses domestic conflicts and the Norman preparation for their second invasion (1105–1107).
[src:vidin/alexiad] addresses Aaron's conspiracy and the second Norman invasion (1107–1108).
[src:vidin/alexiad] The central focus of the *Alexiad* is the reign of Alexios Komnenos from 1081 to 1118.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna presents an idealised portrait of her father's reign centering on his struggles with rivals such as Normans, Pechenegs, Turks, and the Latins of the First Crusade.
[src:vidin/alexiad] While she acknowledges some of her father's faults and repeatedly emphasises her desire to achieve the objectivity suitable to a historian, Anna repeatedly praises him as a model ruler.
[src:vidin/alexiad] His victories are credited to his guile and to divine support, while his defeats are usually softened by accounts of personal valor or of later success resulting from initial setbacks.
[src:vidin/alexiad] He is often compared to figures from classical antiquity, with historians such as Leonora Neville emphasising how "the characterization of Alexios as wily sea captain steering the empire through constant storms with guile and courage strongly recalls Odysseus".
[src:vidin/alexiad] The *Alexiad* was written in Greek in around 1148 and first edited by Possinus in 1651.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna Komnene described herself in the text and openly acknowledges her feelings and opinions for some events, which goes against the typical format of historiography.
[src:vidin/alexiad] She differed widely from Greek prose historians and because of this the book was initially well received; it was subjected to criticism later.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The *Alexiad* interests many historians because Anna wrote it in a different format to the norm of the time.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna Komnene is the only female Greek historiographer of her era and historians are keen to believe that her style of writing owes much to her being a woman.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Despite including herself in the historiography and the other qualities that make her style vastly different from the typical historiography of the era, Anna Komnene's *Alexiad* has been seen as a "straightforward" history.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Dates for the composition of the *Alexiad* range from the 1130s into the early 1150s, but scholars generally prefer a later composition since numerous aspects of the text seem to be critical of Manuel I Komnenos, who only took power in 1143.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The *Alexiad* is an important source for the history of the First Crusade, but Anna wrote shortly after the Second Crusade's passage through Byzantine territory.
[src:vidin/alexiad] She defended the actions of her father half a century earlier, likely in response to criticism of Alexios that sought to contrast the events to Manuel's more recent dealings with the crusaders.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Similarly, her treatment of personages in the 1107-1108 Norman invasion by Bohemond makes indirect reference to the attack on the southern Balkans by Roger II in 1147.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Clear parallels between the *Alexiad* and the *Gesta Roberti Wiscardi*, a Latin history of Robert Guiscard and the Normans in Italy up to the late 1090s, are indicative that Anna had access to either the text or notes by the author, but the precise chain of transmission is unclear.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The relationship between the *Alexiad* and the work of John Zonaras is similarly not clear: John and Anna were writing at the same time and while it is possible that they saw drafts of the other's work, direct influences have been difficult to trace.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The strong overlap in content between parts of the *Alexiad* and the *Hyle Historia* by Anna's husband Nikephoros Bryennios has been explained by the use of common materials as Anna directly disputes many of Bryennios’ ideas.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The reception of Michael Psellos was important in the 1130s-1150s and Anna was part of the literary circle engaging with his works.
[src:vidin/alexiad] In her introduction, Anna Komnene stated her intention to record true events and to give an account of her father's deeds which "do not deserve to be consigned to forgetfulness".
[src:vidin/alexiad] She is aware that in writing her father's history she may be accused of using panegyric language and often tries to remind the reader of her integrity as an impartial reporter of past events.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Emphasis on Alexios as a "specifically Christian emperor", and a moral as well as politically laudable one, is pervasive.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Peter Frankopan compares Alexios' treatment in the text to the techniques of the hagiographical tradition, while contrasting it with the negative portrait of or the absence of, his successors John II and Manuel I.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna discussed the Latins (Normans and "Franks"), whom she described as barbarians.
[src:vidin/alexiad] This distaste extends to the Turks and Armenians.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The *Alexiad* also criticized John II Komnenos for his accession to the throne (in place of Anna herself) following Alexios' death.
[src:vidin/alexiad] From a modern reader's point of view, the inconsistencies in the descriptions of military events and the Empire's misfortunes (partially due to these literary and especially Homeric influences) may seem exaggerated and stereotypical.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Despite these issues, George Ostrogorsky emphasizes the importance of the *Alexiad* as a primary document.
[src:vidin/alexiad] There has been some debate as to whether the *Alexiad* was in fact written by Anna Komnene.
[src:vidin/alexiad] It is largely agreed that Anna Komnene was the author.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Mentions in the text of her engagement, her role as a wife and the commentary on her female modesty that influences her writing make Anna's authorship of the *Alexiad* "unmistakable", according to some scholars.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The predominance of military matters is argued to match Anna's choice to write history in the epic genre, reflecting the cultural influence of her family.
[src:vidin/alexiad] She certainly could have written about military affairs, since she was able to accompany her father, the emperor, on military campaigns.
[src:vidin/alexiad] She names her sources explicitly as "those who accompanied the emperor on campaign", as well as Alexios Komnenos and George Palaiologos, so that "[i]t is not necessary to imagine that she left out a reference to her most important source".
[src:vidin/alexiad] Many scholars believe that the great detail about her father's home life and military style, combined with her experiences and mentions of femininity, provide a strong case for her authorship of the *Alexiad*.
[src:vidin/alexiad] The few passages in the text that can be identified as the author's subjective commentary, aside from emotionally charged references to her husband, hardly betray the author's gender or any other aspect of her background.
[src:vidin/alexiad] This feature was seized on by James Howard-Johnston who argued, controversially, that the *Alexiad* could not have been written by a woman.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Drawing attention to the extensive military sections of the *Alexiad* and suggesting that Anna was merely working from her husband's field notes, Howard-Johnston proposed to rename the work "Nicephoros's *Alexiad*".
[src:vidin/alexiad] However, as Peter Frankopan pointed out, no comparable work by a woman survives from the Byzantine period and "there is no reason why this author should conform to a model set out by the reader" (i.e. to contemporary assumptions about gender).
[src:vidin/alexiad] Women of the aristocracy had more opportunities to pursue higher education, in comparison to those of humble origins, whose education was mainly learning to write and read, memorizing psalms and studying the scriptures.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Some female aristocrats had an interest in literature and would be praised for their depth of knowledge by contemporary writers.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Despite that, Komnene's high education and expertise in secular literature – the study of which was typically discouraged – remained exceptional.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna Komnene's unusual style is noteworthy in that it included a history of her father's actions during the First Crusade and her reactions to some of these events.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Her opinions and commentary on particular events in an otherwise historical text have been assigned to her both positively and negatively.
[src:vidin/alexiad] This interpretation of her histories is known as a "autobiographical history", meaning it is the history of Alexios and her own life in her style, which is not seen in male authors.
[src:vidin/alexiad] While the English historian Edward Gibbon saw this "gendered" narrative to betray "in every page the vanity of a female author".
[src:vidin/alexiad] Other scholars claim this style might be indicative of Anna's mentor, Michael Psellos.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Some take this even further to suggest that Anna used Psellos' *Chronographia* as a model for her narration in her history and took his style even further, suggesting it was not her gender but her influences that led to her writing style.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Anna Komnene is considered unique for her time in the intensity by which she integrates her personal narrative yet does not focus on personal details.
[src:vidin/alexiad] For some modern scholars it is an early example of inverted "gender roles", with a woman taking the lead of a story rather than the typical limitation as a quiet supporting role.
[src:vidin/alexiad] Below is a list of manuscripts containing the complete work or its summary.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] For much of their history, most Jews have lived in diasporas outside of the Land of Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Dispersion has resulted both from voluntary emigration (e.g. to seek employment or improved conditions of life) and from various historical conflicts that have been associated with Jewish persecution, expulsions and exoduses.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In the late 19th century, 99.7% of the world's Jews lived outside the region, with Jews representing 2–5% of the population of the Palestine region.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Despite its historical value as a national aspiration for the Jewish people, *aliyah* was rarely undertaken prior to the "national awakening" and the development of the Zionist movement in the late 19th century.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Larger-scale immigration of Jews to Palestine had consequently begun by 1882.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Since the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, more than 3 million Jews have made *aliyah*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] As of 2014, Israel and the Israeli-occupied territories contain approximately 42.9 percent of the world's Jewish population.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Since 2024, the State of Israel has seen net negative migration: *yerida* is higher than *aliyah*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The Hebrew word *aliyah* means "ascent" or "going up".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Jewish tradition views traveling to the Land of Israel as an ascent, both geographically and metaphysically.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In one opinion, the geographical sense preceded the metaphorical one, as most Jews going on pilgrimage to Jerusalem, which is situated at approximately 750 meters (2,500 feet) above sea level, had to climb to a higher geographic elevation.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The reason is that many Jews in early rabbinic times used to live either in Egypt's Nile Delta and on the plains of Babylonia, which lay relatively low; or somewhere in the Mediterranean Basin, from where they arrived by ship.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Thus, in the Book of Genesis 46 God speaks to Jacob and says “Do not be afraid to *go down* to Egypt, for I will make you into a great nation there.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] I will *go down* to Egypt with you." And in the Book of Exodus 1, the oppressive new King of Egypt suspects the Hebrews of living in Egypt of being enemies who in time of war might "Fight against us, and so get them *up* out of the land".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Widespread use of the term *Aliyah* to describe ideologically inspired Jewish immigration to Palestine / Israel is due to Arthur Ruppin's 1930 work *Soziologie der Juden*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] *Aliyah* has also been defined, by sociologists such as Aryeh Tartakower, as immigration for the good of the community, regardless of the destination.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Sifre says that the *mitzvah* (commandment) of living in Eretz Yisrael is as important as all the other *mitzvot* put together.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] There are many *mitzvot* such as shmita, the sabbatical year for farming, which can only be performed in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] For generations of religious Jews, *aliyah* was associated with the coming of the Jewish Messiah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Jews prayed for their Messiah to come, who was to redeem the "Land of Israel" (*Eretz Yisrael*, commonly known in English as the region of Palestine) from gentile rule and return world Jewry to the land under a Halachic theocracy.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In Zionist discourse, the term *aliyah* (plural *aliyot*) includes both voluntary immigration for ideological, emotional, or practical reasons and, on the other hand, mass flight of persecuted populations of Jews.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The vast majority of Israeli Jews today trace their family's recent roots to outside the country.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] While many have actively chosen to settle in Israel rather than some other country, many had little or no choice about leaving their previous home countries.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] While Israel is commonly recognized as "a country of immigrants", it is also, in large measure, a country of refugees, including internal refugees.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The Hebrew Bible relates that the patriarch Abraham came to the Land of Canaan with his family and followers in approximately 1800 BC.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] His grandson Jacob went down to Egypt with his family, and after several centuries there, the Israelites went back to Canaan under Moses and Joshua, entering it in about 1300 BC.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] A few decades after the fall of the Kingdom of Judah and the Babylonian exile of the Jewish people, approximately 50,000 Jews returned to Zion following the Edict of Cyrus from 538 BC.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The Jewish priestly scribe Ezra led the Jewish exiles living in Babylon to their home city of Jerusalem in 459 BC.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Even those Jews who did not end up returning gave their children names like Yashuv-Tzadik and Yaeliyahu which testified to their desire to return.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Jews returned to the Land of Israel throughout the Second Temple period.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Herod the Great also encouraged *aliyah* and often gave key posts, such as the position of High Priest, to returnees.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In late antiquity, the two hubs of rabbinic learning were Babylonia and the Land of Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Throughout the Amoraic period, many Babylonian Jews immigrated to the Land of Israel and left their mark on life there, as rabbis and leaders.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In the 10th century, leaders of the Karaite Jewish community, mostly living under Persian rule, urged their followers to settle in Eretz Yisrael.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Known as the Mourners of Zion, these Karaites established their own quarter in Jerusalem, on the western slope of the Kidron Valley.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] During this period, there is abundant evidence of pilgrimages to Jerusalem by Jews from various countries, mainly in the month of Tishrei, around the time of the Sukkot holiday.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The number of Jews migrating to the land of Israel rose significantly between the 13th and 19th centuries, mainly due to a general decline in the status of Jews across Europe and an increase in religious persecution.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The expulsion of Jews from England (1290), France (1391), Austria (1421), and Spain (the Alhambra decree of 1492) were seen by many as a sign of approaching redemption and contributed greatly to the messianic spirit of the time.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Aliyah was also spurred during this period by the resurgence of messianic fervor among the Jews of France, Italy, the German states, Poland, Russia, and North Africa.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The belief in the imminent coming of the Jewish Messiah, the ingathering of the exiles and the re-establishment of the kingdom of Israel encouraged many who had few other options to make the perilous journey to the land of Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Pre-Zionist resettlement in Palestine met with various degrees of success.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In 1211, the "aliyah of the three hundred rabbis" saw notable French and German Tosafists such as Samson of Coucy, Joseph ben Baruch, Baruch ben Isaac and Samson ben Abraham of Sens, along with their colleagues and students, immigrate to Palestine, as recorded in the *Shebet Yehudah*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] There is doubt about the accuracy of the account, as there is no evidence that there were actually 300 immigrants, and that number is likely exaggerated.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] It also mentions Jonathan ben David ha-Cohen immigrating there, but he died in 1205, and was said to have celebrated Purim in Palestine in 1210.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Little is known of the fate of their descendants.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] It is thought that few survived the bloody upheavals caused by the Crusader invasion in 1229 and their subsequent expulsion by the Muslims in 1291.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] After the fall of the Byzantine Empire in 1453 and the expulsion of Jews from Spain (1492) and Portugal (1498), many Jews made their way to the Holy Land.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Abraham of Sens, who emigrated in 1211, wrote in his responsa that the biblical commandment to go to Eretz Yisrael was nullified due to *pikuach nefesh*, or saving a life, citing the danger of the journey, particularly for pregnant women.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Haim ben Hananel HaCohen ruled that the commandment was negated altogether.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Moses ben Joseph di Trani, born in Salonika in 1490, made *aliyah* and became the rabbi of Safed, where he died in 1580.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In his writings, Trani disagreed with Haim Cohen, and argued that it was not dangerous to travel to Palestine due to the peace between "Edom" (Christian Europe) and "Ishmael" (Islamic/Arab world) at the time.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] David ibn Zimri, known as the Radbaz, also went to Palestine where he died in 1574.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The Radbaz reconciled Maimonides' brief journey to Jerusalem in 1165, but ultimate settlement in Egypt, despite Maimonides' belief that it was commanded to settle in Eretz Yisrael and forbidden to remain in Egypt, that he had been compelled to remain by the authorities, as physician to the sultan.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Ishtori Haparchi, who was a geographer of Palestine, said that Maimonides signed letters as "the writer who transgresses three negative commandments every day," though no surviving responsa with Maimonides' autograph are found bearing this.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Notable rabbi Nahmanides went to Jerusalem a few years before his death in 1267.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Nahmanides, in his gloss on Maimonides' *Book of Commandments*, articulated that contrary to Rashi's interpretation, settling Eretz Yisrael was a divine commandment and not simply a promise, arguing that the Torah commanded the people of Israel to conquer and possess the Holy Land.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Though he spent most of his life in Gerona, he went to Palestine without his wife and children and died in 1270.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] It not known why his family did not join him.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In 1541, following their expulsion from Naples, some Jews immigrated to Palestine.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In the 1560s, Gracia Mendes and Joseph Nasi obtained a concession from the sultan to permit Jews to settle in Safed and Tiberias.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Some Ukrainian Jewish refugees fleeing the pogroms of the Khmelnytsky Uprising of the mid-17th century also settled in the Holy Land.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Then the immigration in the 18th and early 19th centuries of thousands of followers of various Kabbalist and Hassidic rabbis, as well as the disciples of the Vilna Gaon and the disciples of the Chattam Sofer, added considerably to the Jewish populations in Jerusalem, Tiberias, Hebron, and Safed.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The 1700 immigration associated with messianic Sabbateanism is considered the first modern mass movement of Jewish immigrants to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Also in 1700, Judah HeHasid and his followers settled in Jerusalem, and Hayyim ben Jacob Abulafia and his followers in Tiberias.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] HeHasid's Hurva Synagogue (or "ruined synagogue"), rebuilt on the ruins of a 15th-century synagogue, was again destroyed in 1720.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] A notable emigration of about 300 Hasidic immigrants led by Menachem Mendel of Vitebsk and Abraham Kalisker in 1777 aimed to establish a religious center.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] They were preceded by Nachman of Horodenka, Abraham Gershon of Kitov and Menahem Mendel of Premyshlan in 1764, members of the circle of the Baal Shem Tov.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] The messianic dreams of the Gaon of Vilna inspired one of the largest pre-Zionist waves of immigration to Eretz Yisrael.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] In 1808 hundreds of the Gaon's disciples, known as Perushim, settled in Tiberias and Safed, and later formed the core of the Old Yishuv in Jerusalem.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] There were also those who like the British mystic Laurence Oliphant tried to lease Northern Palestine to settle the Jews there (1879).
[src:vidin/aliyah-p01] Jewish immigration to Palestine began in earnest following the 1839 Tanzimat reforms; between 1840 and 1880, the Jewish population of Palestine rose from 9,000 to 23,000.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In Zionist history, the different waves of *aliyah*, beginning with the arrival of the *Biluim* from Russia in 1882, are categorized by date and the country of origin of the immigrants.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1872 colonies were established at Petah Tikva and Rosh Pinna.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Mikveh Israel agricultural school was established in 1870.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Jewish settlement in Jaffa may be dated to 1820, when Isaiah Ajiman, a merchant hailing from one of several prominent Istanbul Jewish families, moved there from said capital.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the aftermath of the 1826 Auspicious Incident, he and two other leading figures of the Istanbul Jewish community were executed, marking a decline in the status of Ottoman Jews.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Pre-19th century small-scale return migration of Diaspora Jews to the Land of Israel is characterized as the Pre-Modern *Aliyah*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since the birth of Zionism in the late 19th century, the advocates of *aliyah* have striven to facilitate the settlement of Jewish refugees in Ottoman Palestine, Mandatory Palestine, and the sovereign State of Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Over the next two years, discussion in Zionist literature transformed the two prior to refer to the contemporary immigration waves at the end of the 19th century and the early 20th.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] These periods as per the modern convention were first published in October 1919 by Yosef Haim Brenner.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the 1930s and 1940s, Zionist historians began to divide the next periods of immigration to Palestine into different phases, in a form which "created and presumed the unique traits of *aliyah* and the Zionist enterprise".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following Ruppin and Jacob Lestschinsky before him, Gurevich's use of the term Aliyah emphasized the ideological element of the immigration, despite the fact that such a motivation was not representative of the immigrants as a whole.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Today, most aliyah consists of voluntary migration for ideological, economic, or family reunification purposes.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Because Jewish lineage can provide a right to Israeli citizenship, *aliyah* (returning to Israel) has both a secular and a religious significance.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The first modern period of immigration to receive a number in common speech was the Third Aliyah, which in the World War I period was referred to as the successor to the First and Second Aliyot from Babylonia in the Biblical period.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Reference to earlier modern periods as the First and Second Aliyot appeared first in 1919 and took a while to catch on.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The pronounced persecution of Russian Jews between 1881 and 1910 led to a large wave of emigration.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since only a small portion of East European Jews had adopted Zionism by then, between 1881 and 1914 only 30–40,000 emigrants went to Ottoman Palestine, while over one and a half million Russian Jews and 300,000 from Austria-Hungary reached Northern America.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1882 and 1903, approximately 35,000 Jews immigrated to the Ottoman Palestine, joining the pre-existing Jewish population which in 1880 numbered 20,000-25,000.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Jews immigrating arrived in groups that had been assembled, or recruited.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Most of these groups had been arranged in the areas of Romania and Russia in the 1880s.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The migration of Jews from Russia correlates with the end of the Russian pogroms, with about 3 percent of Jews emigrating from Europe to Palestine.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The groups who arrived in Palestine around this time were called *Hibbat Tsiyon*, which is a Hebrew word meaning "fondness for Zion." They were also called *Hovevei Tsiyon* or "enthusiasts for Zion" by the members of the groups themselves.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] While these groups expressed interest and "fondness" for Palestine, they were not strong enough in number to encompass an entire mass movement as would appear later on in other waves of migration.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The majority, belonging to the Hovevei Zion and Bilu movements, came from the Russian Empire with a smaller number arriving from Yemen.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Many established agricultural communities.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Among the towns that these individuals established are Petah Tikva (already in 1878), Rishon LeZion, Rosh Pinna, and Zikhron Ya'akov.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1882 the Yemenite Jews settled in the Arab village of Silwan located south-east of the walls of the Old City of Jerusalem on the slopes of the Mount of Olives.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Kurdish Jews settled in Jerusalem starting around 1895.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The vast majority came from the Russian Empire, in particular from the Pale of Settlement in Eastern Europe.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Jews from other countries in Eastern Europe such as Romania and Bulgaria also joined.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Jewish emigration from Eastern Europe was largely due to pogroms and outbreaks of antisemitism there.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] However, Mountain Jews from the Caucasus and Jews from other countries including Yemen, Iran, and Argentina also arrived at this time.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Ahuzat Bayit, a new suburb of Jaffa established in 1909, eventually grew to become the city of Tel Aviv.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During this period, some of the underpinnings of an independent nation-state arose: Hebrew, the ancient national language, was revived as a spoken language; newspapers and literature written in Hebrew were published; political parties and workers organizations were established.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The First World War effectively ended the period of the Second Aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] It is estimated that over half of those who arrived during this period ended up leaving; Ben Gurion stated that nine out of ten left.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1919 and 1923, 40,000 Jews, mainly from Eastern Europe, arrived in the wake of World War I.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The British occupation of Palestine and the establishment of the British Mandate created the conditions for the implementation of the promises contained in the Balfour Declaration.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Many of the Jewish immigrants were ideologically driven pioneers, known as *halutzim*, trained in agriculture and capable of establishing self-sustaining economies.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In spite of immigration quotas established by the British administration, the Jewish population reached 90,000 by the end of this period.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Jezreel Valley and the Hefer Plain marshes were drained and converted to agricultural use.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Additional national institutions arose such as the Histadrut (General Labor Federation); an elected assembly; national council; and the Haganah, a Zionist paramilitary organization.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1924 and 1929, 82,000 Jews arrived, many as a result of increasing anti-Semitism in Poland and throughout Europe.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The vast majority of Jewish immigrants arrived from Europe mostly from Poland, the Soviet Union, Romania, and Lithuania, but about 12% came from Asia, mostly Yemen and Iraq.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The immigration quotas of the United States kept Jews out.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This group contained many middle-class families that moved to the growing towns, establishing small businesses, and light industry.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Of these approximately 23,000 left the country.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1929 and 1939, with the rise of Nazism in Germany, a new wave of 250,000 immigrants arrived; the majority of these, 174,000, arrived between 1933 and 1936, after which increasing restrictions on immigration by the British made immigration clandestine and illegal, called *Aliyah Bet*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Fifth Aliyah was again driven almost entirely from Europe, mostly from Central Europe (particularly from Poland, Germany, Austria, and Czechoslovakia), but also from Greece.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Some Jewish immigrants also came from other countries such as Turkey, Iran, and Yemen.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Fifth Aliyah contained large numbers of professionals, doctors, lawyers, and professors, from Germany.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Refugee architects and musicians introduced the Bauhaus style (the White City of Tel Aviv has the highest concentration of International Style architecture in the world with a strong element of Bauhaus) and founded the Palestine Philharmonic Orchestra.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] With the completion of the port at Haifa and its oil refineries, significant industry was added to the predominantly agricultural economy.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Jewish population reached 450,000 by 1940.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] At the same time, tensions between Arabs and Jews grew during this period, leading to a series of Arab riots against the Jews in 1929 that left many dead and resulted in the depopulation of the Jewish community in Hebron.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This was followed by more violence during the "Great Uprising" of 1936–1939.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In response to the ever-increasing tension between the Arabic and Jewish communities married with the various commitments the British faced at the dawn of World War II, the British issued the White Paper of 1939, which severely restricted Jewish immigration to 75,000 people for five years.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This served to create a *relatively* peaceful eight years in Palestine while the Holocaust unfolded in Europe.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Shortly after their rise to power, the Nazis negotiated the Ha'avara or "Transfer" Agreement with the Jewish Agency under which 50,000 German Jews and $100 million worth of their assets would be moved to Palestine.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The British government limited Jewish immigration to Mandatory Palestine with quotas, and following the rise of Nazism to power in Germany, illegal immigration to Mandatory Palestine commenced.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The illegal immigration was known as *Aliyah Bet* ("secondary immigration"), or *Ha'apalah*, and was organized by the Mossad Le'aliyah Bet, as well as by the Irgun.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Immigration was done mainly by sea, and to a lesser extent overland through Iraq and Syria.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During World War II and the years that followed until independence, *Aliyah Bet* became the main form of Jewish immigration to Mandatory Palestine.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following the war, Bricha ("escape"), an organization of former partisans and ghetto fighters was primarily responsible for smuggling Jews from Eastern Europe through Poland.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1946 Poland was the only Eastern Bloc country to allow free Jewish aliyah to Mandate Palestine without visas or exit permits.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] By contrast, Stalin forcibly brought Soviet Jews back who lived in occupied or soviet territory to USSR, as agreed by the Allies during the Yalta Conference.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The refugees were sent to the Italian ports from which they traveled to Mandatory Palestine.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] More than 4,500 survivors left the French port of Sète aboard *President Warfield* (renamed *Exodus*).
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The British turned them back to France from Haifa, and forced them ashore in Hamburg.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Despite British efforts to curb the illegal immigration, during the 14 years of its operation, 110,000 Jews immigrated to Palestine.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1945 reports of the Holocaust with its 6 million Jewish killed, caused many Jews in Palestine to turn openly against the British Mandate, and illegal immigration escalated rapidly as many Holocaust survivors joined the aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] After Aliyah Bet, the process of numbering or naming individual aliyot ceased, but immigration did not.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] A major wave of Jewish immigration, mainly from post-Holocaust Europe and the Arab and Muslim world took place from 1948 to 1951.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In three and a half years, the Jewish population of Israel, which was 650,000 at the state's founding, was more than doubled by an influx of about 688,000 immigrants.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1949, the largest-ever number of Jewish immigrants in a single year—249,954—arrived in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This period of immigration is often termed *kibbutz galuyot* (literally, ingathering of exiles), due to the large number of Jewish diaspora communities that made aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] However, *kibbutz galuyot* can also refer to aliyah in general.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] At the beginning of the immigration wave, most of the immigrants to reach Israel were Holocaust survivors from Europe, including many from displaced persons camps in Germany, Austria, and Italy, and from British detention camps on Cyprus.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Large sections of shattered Jewish communities throughout Europe, such as those from Poland and Romania also immigrated to Israel, with some communities, such as those from Bulgaria and Yugoslavia, being almost entirely transferred.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] At the same time, the number of Jewish immigrants from Arab countries greatly increased.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Special operations were undertaken to evacuate Jewish communities perceived to be in serious danger to Israel, such as Operation Magic Carpet, which evacuated almost the entire Jewish population of Yemen, and Operation Ezra and Nehemiah, which airlifted most of the Jews of Iraq to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Egyptian Jews were smuggled to Israel in Operation Goshen.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Nearly the entire Jewish population of Libya left for Israel around this time, and clandestine aliyah from Syria took place, as the Syrian government prohibited Jewish emigration, in a process that was to last decades.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Israel also saw significant immigration of Jews from non-Arab Muslim countries such as Iran, Turkey, and Afghanistan in this period.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] To ensure that Israel, which at that time had a small economy and scant foreign currency reserves, could provide for the immigrants, a strict regime of rationing was put in place.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Measures were enacted to ensure that all Israeli citizens had access to adequate food, housing, and clothing.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Austerity was very restrictive until 1953; the previous year, Israel had signed a reparations agreement with West Germany, in which the West German government would pay Israel as compensation for the Holocaust, due to Israel's taking in a large number of Holocaust survivors.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The resulting influx of foreign capital boosted the Israeli economy and allowed for the relaxing of most restrictions.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The remaining austerity measures were gradually phased out throughout the following years.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] When new immigrants arrived in Israel, they were sprayed with DDT, underwent a medical examination, were inoculated against diseases, and were given food.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The earliest immigrants received desirable homes in established urban areas, but most of the immigrants were then sent to transit camps, known initially as immigrant camps, and later as *Ma'abarot*.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Many were also initially housed in reception centers in military barracks.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] By the end of 1950, some 93,000 immigrants were housed in 62 transit camps.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Israeli government's goal was to get the immigrants out of refugee housing and into society as speedily as possible.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Immigrants who left the camps received a ration card, an identity card, a mattress, a pair of blankets, and $21 to $36 in cash.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] They settled either in established cities and towns, or in kibbutzim and moshavim.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Many others stayed in the *Ma'abarot* as they were gradually turned into permanent cities and towns, which became known as development towns, or were absorbed as neighborhoods of the towns they were attached to, and the tin dwellings were replaced with permanent housing.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the early 1950s, the immigration wave subsided, and emigration increased; ultimately, some 10% of the immigrants would leave Israel for other countries in the following years.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1953, immigration to Israel averaged 1,200 a month, while emigration averaged 700 a month.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The end of the period of mass immigration gave Israel a critical opportunity to more rapidly absorb the immigrants still living in transit camps.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Israeli government built 260 new settlements and 78,000 housing units to accommodate the immigrants, and by the mid-1950s, almost all were in permanent housing.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the mid-1950s, a smaller wave of immigration began from North African countries such as Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria, and Egypt, many of which were in the midst of nationalist struggles.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1952 and 1964, some 240,000 North African Jews came to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During this period, smaller but significant numbers arrived from other places such as Europe, Iran, India, and Latin America.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In particular, a small immigration wave from then communist Poland, known as the "Gomulka Aliyah", took place during this period.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] From 1956 to 1960, Poland permitted free Jewish emigration, and some 50,000 Polish Jews immigrated to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since the founding of the State of Israel, the Jewish Agency for Israel was mandated as the organization responsible for aliyah in the diaspora.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] From 1948 until the early 1970s, around 900,000 Jews from Arab lands left, fled, or were expelled from various Arab nations, of which an estimated 650,000 settled in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the course of Operation Magic Carpet (1949–1950), nearly the entire community of Yemenite Jews (about 49,000) immigrated to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Some 120,000 Iraqi Jews were airlifted to Israel in Operation Ezra and Nehemiah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following the establishment of Israel, about one-third of Iranian Jews, most of them poor, immigrated to Israel, and immigration from Iran continued throughout the following decades.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] An estimated 70,000 Iranian Jews immigrated to Israel between 1948 and 1978.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following the Islamic Revolution in 1979, most of the Iranian Jewish community left, with some 20,000 Iranian Jews immigrating to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Many Iranian Jews also settled in the United States (especially in New York City and Los Angeles).
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The first major wave of aliyah from Ethiopia took place in the mid-1970s.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The massive airlift known as Operation Moses began to bring Ethiopian Jews to Israel on November 18, 1984, and ended on January 5, 1985.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During those six weeks, some 6,500–8,000 Ethiopian Jews were flown from Sudan to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] An estimated 2,000–4,000 Jews died en route to Sudan or in Sudanese refugee camps.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1991 Operation Solomon was launched to bring the Beta Israel Jews of Ethiopia.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In one day, May 24, 34 aircraft landed at Addis Ababa and brought 14,325 Jews from Ethiopia to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since that time, Ethiopian Jews have continued to immigrate to Israel bringing the number of Ethiopian-Israelis today to over 100,000.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] After the war, Romania had second-largest Jewish population in Europe, of around 350,000 or higher.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1949, 118,939 Romanian Jews had immigrated to Israel since the war ended.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Romanian Jews were, under their own will, "sold" or "exchanged" to Israel in the 1950s with the help of the American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee for about 8,000 lei (about 420 dollars).
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The price of these Jews usually varied according to their "worth".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This practice continued at a slower pace from 1965 under Nicolae Ceaușescu, a Romanian communist leader.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During the 1950s, West Germany had been also paying Romania an amount of money in exchange for some Germans of Romania, and, just like the Jews (both of which were regarded as "co-nationals"), their price was "calculated".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Ceaușescu, happy with these policies, even declared that "oil, Germans, and Jews are our most important export commodities".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Israeli government paid to facilitate aliyah, and around 235,000 people emigrated from Romania to Israel under this agreement.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] When Romania was under control of Gheorghe Gheorghiu-Dej, he received 10 million dollars per year, and only he had the access to the money transferred to the secret account.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Israel also bought Romanian goods and invested into Romania's economy.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] After his death, Ceauşescu practically sold the Jews to Israel, and received between 4,000 and $6,000 per person.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Israel could have transferred nearly 60 million dollars for the aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] A mass emigration was politically undesirable for the Soviet regime.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The only acceptable ground was family reunification, and a formal petition ("вызов", *vyzov*) from a relative from abroad was required for the processing to begin.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The risks to apply for an exit visa compounded because the entire family had to quit their jobs, which in turn would make them vulnerable to charges of social parasitism, a criminal offense.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Because of these hardships, Israel set up the group Lishkat Hakesher in the early 1950s to maintain contact and promote aliyah with Jews behind the Iron Curtain.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] From Israel's establishment in 1948 to the Six-Day War in 1967, Soviet aliyah remained minimal.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Those who made aliyah during this period were mainly elderly people granted clearance to leave for family reunification purposes.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Only about 22,000 Soviet Jews managed to reach Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the wake of the Six-Day War, the USSR broke off the diplomatic relations with the Jewish state.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] An Anti-Zionist propaganda campaign in the state-controlled mass media and the rise of Zionology were accompanied by harsher discrimination of the Soviet Jews.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] After the Dymshits-Kuznetsov hijacking affair and the crackdown that followed, strong international condemnations caused the Soviet authorities to increase the emigration quota.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the years 1960–1970, the USSR let only 4,000 people leave; in the following decade, the number rose to 250,000.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The exodus of Soviet Jews began in 1968.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1968 and 1973, almost all Soviet Jews allowed to leave settled in Israel, and only a small minority moved to other Western countries.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] However, in the following years, the number of those moving to other Western nations increased.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Soviet Jews granted permission to leave were taken by train to Austria to be processed and then flown to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] There, the ones who chose not to go to Israel, called "dropouts", exchanged their immigrant invitations to Israel for refugee status in a Western country, especially the United States.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Eventually, most Soviet Jews granted permission to leave became dropouts.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Overall, between 1970 and 1988, some 291,000 Soviet Jews were granted exit visas, of whom 165,000 moved to Israel and 126,000 moved to the United States.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1989 a record 71,000 Soviet Jews were granted exodus from the USSR, of whom only 12,117 immigrated to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1989 the United States changed its immigration policy of unconditionally granting Soviet Jews refugee status.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] That same year, Soviet Premier Mikhail Gorbachev ended restrictions on Jewish immigration, and the Soviet Union itself collapsed in 1991.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since then, about a million people from the former Soviet Union immigrated to Israel, including approximately 240,000 who were not Jewish according to rabbinical law, but were eligible for Israeli citizenship under the Law of Return.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The number of immigrants counted as halachically non-Jewish from the former USSR has been constantly rising ever since 1989.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] For example, in 1990 around 96% of the immigrants were halachically Jewish and only 4% were non-Jewish family members.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following the beginning of the Russo-Ukrainian War, Ukrainian Jews making aliyah from Ukraine reached 142% higher during the first four months of 2014 compared to the previous year.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The wave of aliyah from Russia since 2014 has been called "Putin's aliyah", "Putin's exodus", and "cheese aliyah" (foreign cheese was one of the first products to disappear from Russian shops because of anti-sanctions imposed by the Russian government).
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The number of repatriants in this wave is comparable with that coming from the USSR between 1970 and 1988.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Israel announced "Immigrants Come Home" operation.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] As of June 2022, more than 25,000 people arrived in Israel from Ukraine, Russia, Belarus and Moldova.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In Argentina, the political and economic crisis of 1999–2002 led to a severe banking collapse, resulting in the loss of billions of dollars in deposits and significantly affecting the country's middle class.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During this period, most of the estimated 200,000 Jews in Argentina were directly impacted.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Approximately 4,400 individuals chose to start anew and immigrate to Israel, where they saw new opportunities.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since 2000, over 10,000 Argentine Jews have moved to Israel, joining the thousands of Argentine immigrants who had already settled there.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In Uruguay, the Jewish community, which had reached its peak in the 1960s, began to decline in the 1970s due to a period of political turmoil.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] However, by the early 21st century, following an economic crisis, a portion of the country's Jewish community chose to make aliyah, with approximately 22,000 members remaining in Uruguay.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] It continued to be one of the largest Jewish communities on the continent, both in terms of absolute numbers and as a percentage of the total population.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During 2002 and 2003 the Jewish Agency for Israel launched an intensive public campaign to promote aliyah from the region, and offered additional economic aid for immigrants from Argentina.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Although the economy of Argentina improved, and some who had immigrated to Israel from Argentina moved back following South American country's economic growth from 2003 onwards, Argentine Jews continue to immigrate to Israel, albeit in smaller numbers than before.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Argentine community in Israel is about 50,000-70,000 people, the largest Latin American group in the country.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In Venezuela, growing antisemitism in the country, including antisemitic violence, caused an increasing number of Jews to move to Israel during the 2000s.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] For the first time in Venezuelan history, Jews began leaving for Israel in the hundreds.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] By November 2010, more than half of Venezuela's 20,000-strong Jewish community had left the country.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] From 2000 to 2009, more than 13,000 French Jews immigrated to Israel, largely as a result of growing anti-semitism in the country.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] A peak was reached in 2005, with 2,951 immigrants.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] However, between 20 and 30% eventually returned to France.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 2012, some 200,000 French citizens lived in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During the same year, following the election of François Hollande and the Jewish school shooting in Toulouse, as well as ongoing acts of anti-semitism and the European economic crisis, an increasing number of French Jews began buying property in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In August 2012, it was reported that anti-semitic attacks had risen by 40% in the five months following the Toulouse shooting, and that many French Jews were seriously considering immigrating to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 2013, 3,120 French Jews immigrated to Israel, marking a 63% increase over the previous year.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In the first two months of 2014, French Jewish aliyah increased precipitously by 312% with 854 French Jews making aliyah over the first two months.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Immigration from France throughout 2014 has been attributed to several factors, of which includes increasing antisemitism, in which many Jews have been harassed and attacked by a fusillade of local thugs and gangs, a stagnant European economy and concomitant high youth unemployment rates.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During the first few months of 2014, The Jewish Agency of Israel continued to encourage an increase of French aliyah through aliyah fairs, Hebrew language courses, sessions which help potential immigrants to find jobs in Israel, and immigrant absorption in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] A May 2014 survey revealed that 74 percent of French Jews considered leaving France for Israel; of those considering leaving, 29.9 percent cited anti-Semitism.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Another 24.4 cited their desire to “preserve their Judaism,” while 12.4 percent said they were attracted by other countries. “Economic considerations” was cited by 7.5 percent of the respondents.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] By June 2014, it was estimated by the end of 2014 a full 1 percent of the French Jewish community will have made aliyah to Israel, the largest in a single year.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] During the Hebrew year 5774 (September 2013 - September 2014) for the first time ever, more Jews made aliyah from France than any other country, numbering approximately 6,000 and fleeing antisemitism, violence and economic malaise.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In January 2015, events such as the Charlie Hebdo shooting and Porte de Vincennes hostage crisis created a shock wave of fear across the French Jewish community.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] As a result of these events, the Jewish Agency planned an aliyah plan for 120,000 French Jews who wished to make aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In addition, with Europe's stagnant economy, many affluent French Jewish skilled professionals, businesspeople and investors sought Israel as a start-up haven for international investments, as well as for job and new business opportunities.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In addition, Dov Maimon, a French Jewish émigré who studies migration as a senior fellow at the Jewish People Policy Institute, expects as many as 250,000 French Jews to make aliyah by 2030.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Immigration from France increased: in the first half of 2015, approximately 5,100 French Jews made aliyah to Israel, or 25% more than in the same period during the previous year.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following the November 2015 Paris attacks committed by suspected ISIS affiliates in retaliation for Opération Chammal, one source reported that 80 percent of French Jews were considering making aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] According to the Jewish Agency, nearly 6,500 French Jews made aliyah between January and November 2015.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] More than 200,000 North American immigrants live in Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] There has been a steady flow of immigration from North America since Israel's inception in 1948.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Several thousand American Jews moved to Mandate Palestine before the State of Israel was established.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] From Israel's establishment in 1948 to the Six-Day War in 1967, aliyah from the United States and Canada was minimal.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 1959, a former President of the Association of Americans and Canadians in Israel estimated that out of the 35,000 American and Canadian Jews who had made aliyah, only 6,000 remained.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Following the Six-Day War in 1967, and the subsequent euphoria among world Jewry, significant numbers arrived in the late 1960s and 1970s, whereas it had been a mere trickle before.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Between 1967 and 1973, 60,000 North American Jews immigrated to Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] However, many of them later returned to their original countries.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] An estimated 58% of American Jews who immigrated to Israel between 1961 and 1972 ended up returning to the United States.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Like Western European immigrants, North Americans tend to immigrate to Israel more for religious, ideological, and political purposes, and not financial or security ones.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Many immigrants began arriving in Israel after the First and Second Intifada, with a total of 3,052 arriving in 2005 — the highest number since 1983.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Nefesh B'Nefesh, founded in 2002 by Rabbi Yehoshua Fass and Tony Gelbart, works to encourage aliyah from North America and the UK by providing financial assistance, employment services and streamlined governmental procedures.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Nefesh B’Nefesh works in cooperation with the Jewish Agency and the Israeli Government in increasing the numbers of North American and British immigrants.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] After the 2008 financial crisis, American Jewish immigration to Israel rose.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This wave of immigration was triggered by Israel's lower unemployment rate, combined with financial incentives offered to new Jewish immigrants.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 2009, aliyah was at its highest in 36 years, with 3,324 North American Jews making aliyah.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Since the mid-1990s, there has been a steady stream of South African, American and French Jews who have either made aliyah, or purchased property in Israel for potential future immigration.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Over 2,000 French Jews moved to Israel each year between 2000 and 2004 due to anti-Semitism in France.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Bnei Menashe Jews from India, whose recent discovery and recognition by mainstream Judaism as descendants of the Ten Lost Tribes is subject to some controversy, slowly started their aliyah in the early 1990s and continue arriving in slow numbers.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Organizations such as Nefesh B'Nefesh and Shavei Israel help with aliyah by supporting financial aid and guidance on a variety of topics such as finding work, learning Hebrew, and assimilation into Israeli culture.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In early 2007 *Haaretz* reported that aliyah for the year of 2006 was down approximately 9% from 2005, "the lowest number of immigrants recorded since 1988".
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The number of new immigrants in 2007 was 18,127, the lowest since 1988.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Only 36% of these new immigrants came from the former Soviet Union (close to 90% in the 1990s) while the number of immigrants from countries like France and the United States was stable.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] On October 20, 2009, the first group of Kaifeng Jews arrived in Israel, in an aliyah operation coordinated by Shavei Israel.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] *Shalom Life* reported that over 19,000 new immigrants arrived in Israel in 2010, an increase of 16 percent over 2009.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] As reported by the Ministry of Immigration and Refugees, there has been a decline in immigration to Israel since the onset of Hamas' conflict with Israel on October 7, 2023.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The ministry indicates that immigration to Israel in 2023 has fallen by 30% in comparison to 2024.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Central Bureau of Statistics announced in December 2024 that 82,700 Israelis departed from the country in the previous year, marking a notable rise compared to the year before and indicating a deceleration in population growth.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] This was the first instance in which the bureau incorporated long-term foreign residents into its census data.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] In 2013, the office of the Prime Minister of Israel announced that some people born out of wedlock, "wishing to immigrate to Israel could be subjected to DNA testing" to prove their paternity is as they claim.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] A Foreign Ministry spokesman said the genetic paternity testing idea is based on the recommendations of Nativ, an Israeli government organization that has helped Soviet and post-Soviet Jews with aliyah since the 1950s.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The holiday was also established to acknowledge Aliyah, immigration to the Jewish state, as a core value of the State of Israel, and honor the ongoing contributions of Olim, Jewish immigrants, to Israeli society.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Yom HaAliyah is also observed in Israeli schools on the seventh of the Hebrew month of Cheshvan.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The original day chosen for Yom HaAliyah, the tenth of Nisan, is laden with symbolism.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Although a modern holiday created by the Knesset of Israel, the tenth of Nisan is a date of religious significance for the Jewish People as recounted in the Hebrew Bible and in traditional Jewish thought.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] On the tenth of Nisan, according to the biblical narrative in the Book of Joshua, Joshua and the Israelites crossed the Jordan River at Gilgal into the Promised Land while carrying the Ark of the Covenant.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] It was thus the first documented "mass aliyah." On that day, God commanded the Israelites to commemorate and celebrate the occasion by erecting twelve stones with the text of the Torah engraved upon them.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The stones represented the entirety of the Jewish nation's twelve tribes and their gratitude for God's gift of the Land of Israel (Hebrew: אֶרֶץ יִשְׂרָאֵל, Modern: *Eretz Yisrael*, Tiberian: *ʼÉreṣ Yiśrāʼēl*) to them.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] Yom HaAliyah, as a modern holiday celebration, began in 2009 as a grassroots community initiative and young Olim self-initiated movement in Tel Aviv, spearheaded by the TLV Internationals organization of the Am Yisrael Foundation.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] On June 21, 2016, the Twentieth Knesset voted in favor of codifying the grassroots initiative into law by officially adding Yom HaAliyah to the Israeli national calendar.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p02] The Yom HaAliyah bill was co-sponsored by Knesset members from different parties in a rare instance of cooperation across the political spectrum of the opposition and coalition.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p03] The number of immigrants since 1882 by period, continent of birth, and country of birth is given in the table below.
[src:vidin/aliyah-p03] Continent of birth and country of birth data is almost always unavailable or nonexistent for before 1919.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] During the 5th century, the Western Empire experienced a significant reduction of its territory.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Vandals conquered North Africa, the Visigoths claimed the southern part of Gaul, Gallaecia was taken by the Suebi, Britannia was abandoned by the central government, and the Empire suffered further from the invasions of Attila, chief of the Huns.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] General Orestes refused to meet the demands of the barbarian "allies" who now formed the army, and tried to expel them from Italy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Unhappy with this, their chieftain Odoacer defeated and killed Orestes, invaded Ravenna and dethroned Romulus Augustus, son of Orestes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] This event of 476, usually marks the end of Classical antiquity and beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman noble and former emperor Julius Nepos continued to rule as emperor from Dalmatia even after the deposition of Romulus Augustus until his death in 480.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Some historians consider him to be the last emperor of the Western Empire instead of Romulus Augustus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After 1200 years of independence and nearly 700 years as a great power, the rule of Rome in the West ended.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Various reasons for Rome's fall have been proposed, including loss of Republicanism, moral decay, military tyranny, class war, slavery, economic stagnation, environmental change, disease, the decline of the Roman race, as well as the inevitable ebb and flow that all civilisations experience.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Empire survived for almost 1000 years after the fall of its Western counterpart and became the most stable Christian realm during the Middle Ages.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] During the 6th century, Justinian reconquered the Italian peninsula from the Ostrogoths, North Africa from the Vandals, and southern Hispania from the Visigoths.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] But within a few years of Justinian's death, Byzantine possessions in Italy were greatly reduced by the Lombards who settled in the peninsula.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the east, partially due to the weakening effect of the Plague of Justinian as well as a series of mutually destructive wars against the Persian Sassanian Empire, the Byzantines were threatened by the rise of Islam.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Its followers rapidly brought about the conquest of the Levant, the conquest of North Africa and the conquest of Egypt during the Arab–Byzantine wars, and soon presented a direct threat to Constantinople.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the following century, the Arabs captured southern Italy and Sicily.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In the west, Slavic populations penetrated deep into the Balkans.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Byzantine Romans, however, managed to stop further Islamic expansion into their lands during the 8th century and, beginning in the 9th century, reclaimed parts of the conquered lands.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] In 1000 AD, the Eastern Empire was at its height: Basil II reconquered Bulgaria and Armenia, and culture and trade flourished.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] However, soon after, this expansion was abruptly stopped in 1071 with the Byzantine defeat in the Battle of Manzikert.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The aftermath of this battle sent the empire into a protracted period of decline.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] Two decades of internal strife and Turkic invasions ultimately led Emperor Alexios I Komnenos to send a call for help to the Western European kingdoms in 1095.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The West responded with the Crusades, eventually resulting in the Sack of Constantinople by participants of the Fourth Crusade.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of Constantinople in 1204 fragmented what remained of the Empire into successor states; the ultimate victor was the Empire of Nicaea.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] After the recapture of Constantinople by Imperial forces, the Empire was little more than a Greek state confined to the Aegean coast.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire collapsed when Mehmed the Conqueror conquered Constantinople on 29 May 1453.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The imperial city of Rome was the largest urban center in the empire, with a population variously estimated from 450,000 to close to one million.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Around 20% of the population under jurisdiction of ancient Rome (25–40%, depending on the standards used, in Roman Italy) lived in innumerable urban centers, with population of 10,000 and more and several military settlements, a very high rate of urbanisation by pre-industrial standards.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Most of those centers had a forum, temples, and other buildings similar to Rome's.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The average life expectancy in the Middle Empire was about 26–28 years.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The roots of the legal principles and practices of the ancient Romans may be traced to the Law of the Twelve Tables promulgated in 449 BC and to the codification of law issued by order of Emperor Justinian I around 530 AD (see *Corpus Juris Civilis*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law as preserved in Justinian's codes continued into the Byzantine Roman Empire, and formed the basis of similar codifications in continental Western Europe.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law continued, in a broader sense, to be applied throughout most of Europe until the end of the 17th century.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The major divisions of the law of ancient Rome, as contained within the Justinian and Theodosian law codes, consisted of *Jus civile*, *Jus gentium*, and *Jus naturale*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus civile* ('citizen law') was the body of common laws that applied to Roman citizens.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Urbanus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus gentium* ('law of nations') was the body of common laws that applied to foreigners, and their dealings with Roman citizens.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Peregrinus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens and foreigners.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] *Jus naturale* encompassed natural law, the body of laws that were considered common to all beings.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society is largely viewed as hierarchical, with slaves (*servi*) at the bottom, freedmen (*liberti*) above them, and free-born citizens (*cives*) at the top.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The broadest, and earliest, division was between the patricians, who could trace their ancestry to one of the 100 patriarchs at the founding of the city, and the plebeians, who could not.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] This became less important in the later Republic, as some plebeian families became wealthy and entered politics, and some patrician families fell economically.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Anyone, patrician or plebeian, who could count a consul as his ancestor was a noble (*nobilis*); a man who was the first of his family to hold the consulship, such as Marius or Cicero, was known as a *novus homo* ('new man') and ennobled his descendants.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Patrician ancestry, however, still conferred considerable prestige, and many religious offices remained restricted to patricians.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] A class division originally based on military service became more important.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Membership of these classes was determined periodically by the censors, according to property.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The wealthiest were the Senatorial class, who dominated politics and command of the army.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Next came the equestrians (*equites*, sometimes translated "knights"), originally those who could afford a warhorse, and who formed a powerful mercantile class.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Several further classes, originally based on the military equipment their members could afford, followed, with the *proletarii*, citizens who had no property other than their children, at the bottom.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Before the reforms of Marius they were ineligible for military service and are often described as being just above freed slaves in wealth and prestige.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Voting power in the Republic depended on class.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Citizens were enrolled in voting "tribes", but the tribes of the richer classes had fewer members than the poorer ones, all the *proletarii* being enrolled in a single tribe.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Voting was done in class order, from top down, and stopped as soon as most of the tribes had been reached, so the poorer classes were often unable to cast their votes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Women in ancient Rome shared some basic rights with their male counterparts, but were not fully regarded as citizens and were thus not allowed to vote or take part in politics.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] At the same time the limited rights of women were gradually expanded (due to emancipation) and women reached freedom from *pater familias*, gained property rights and even had more juridical rights than their husbands, but still no voting rights, and were absent from politics.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Allied foreign cities were often given the Latin Rights, an intermediary level between full citizens and foreigners (*peregrini*), which gave their citizens rights under Roman law and allowed their leading magistrates to become full Roman citizens.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] While there were varying degrees of Latin rights, the main division was between those *cum suffragio* ('with vote'; enrolled in a Roman tribe and able to take part in the *comitia tributa*) and *sine suffragio* ('without vote'; could not take part in Roman politics).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, there were no public schools, so boys were taught to read and write by their parents, or by educated slaves, called *paedagogi*, usually of Greek origin.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The primary aim of education during this period was to train young men in agriculture, warfare, Roman traditions, and public affairs.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Young boys learned much about civic life by accompanying their fathers to religious and political functions, including the Senate for the sons of nobles.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The sons of nobles were apprenticed to a prominent political figure at the age of 16, and campaigned with the army from the age of 17.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Educational practices were modified after the conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms in the 3rd century BC and the resulting Greek influence, although Roman educational practices were still much different from Greek ones.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning at age 12, students went to secondary schools, where the teacher (now called a *grammaticus*) taught them about Greek and Roman literature.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] At the age of 16, some students went on to rhetoric school (where the teacher, usually Greek, was called a *rhetor*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Education at this level prepared students for legal careers, and required that the students memorise the laws of Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Initially, Rome was ruled by kings, who were elected from each of Rome's major tribes in turn.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The exact nature of the king's power is uncertain.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] He may have held near-absolute power, or may have merely been the chief executive of the Senate and the people.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In military matters, the king's authority (*Imperium*) was likely absolute.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] He was also the head of the state religion.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The class struggles of the Roman Republic resulted in an unusual mixture of democracy and oligarchy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The word republic comes from the Latin *res publica*, which literally translates to 'public business'.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman laws traditionally could only be passed by a vote of the Popular assembly (Comitia Tributa).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Likewise, candidates for public positions had to run for election by the people.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, the Roman Senate represented an oligarchic institution, which acted as an advisory body.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the Republic, the Senate held actual authority (*auctoritas*), but no real legislative power; it was technically only an advisory council.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, as the Senators were individually very influential, it was difficult to accomplish anything against the collective will of the Senate.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] New senators were chosen from among the most accomplished patricians by censors (*Censura*), who could also remove a senator from his office if he was found "morally corrupt".
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Later, under the reforms of the dictator Sulla, quaestors were made automatic members of the Senate, though most of his reforms did not survive.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Republic had no fixed bureaucracy, and collected taxes through the practice of tax farming.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Government positions such as quaestor, aedile, or praefect were funded by the office-holder.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] To prevent any citizen from gaining too much power, new magistrates were elected annually and had to share power with a colleague.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] For example, under normal conditions, the highest authority was held by two consuls.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In an emergency, a temporary dictator could be appointed.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the Republic, the administrative system was revised several times to comply with new demands.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the end, it proved inefficient for controlling the ever-expanding dominion of Rome, contributing to the establishment of the Roman Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Empire, the pretense of a republican form of government was maintained.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman emperor was portrayed as only a *princeps*, or 'first citizen', and the Senate gained legislative power and all legal authority previously held by the popular assemblies.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, the rule of the Emperors became increasingly autocratic, and the Senate was reduced to an advisory body appointed by the Emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire did not inherit a set bureaucracy from the Republic, since the Republic did not have any permanent governmental structures apart from the Senate.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor appointed assistants and advisers, but the state lacked many institutions, such as a centrally planned budget.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have cited this as a significant reason for the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] 500 BC) was, like those of other contemporary city-states influenced by Greek civilisation, a citizen *militia* that practised hoplite tactics.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] It was small and organised in five classes (in parallel to the *comitia centuriata*, the body of citizens organised politically), with three providing hoplites and two providing light infantry.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The early Roman army was tactically limited and its stance during this period was essentially defensive.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] By the 3rd century BC, the Romans abandoned the hoplite formation in favour of a more flexible system in which smaller groups of 120 (or sometimes 60) men called '*maniples* could manoeuvre more independently on the battlefield.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Thirty maniples arranged in three lines with supporting troops constituted a legion, totalling between 4,000 and 5,000 men.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The early Republican legion consisted of five sections: manipular heavy infantry (*hastati*, *principes* and *triarii*), a force of light infantry (*velites*), and the cavalry (*equites*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] With the new organisation came a new orientation toward the offensive and a much more aggressive posture toward adjoining city-states.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Until the late Republican period, the typical legionary was a property-owning citizen farmer from a rural area (an *adsiduus*) who served for particular (often annual) campaigns, and who supplied his own equipment.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] After 200 BC, economic conditions in rural areas deteriorated as manpower needs increased, so that the property qualifications for compulsory service were gradually reduced.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning in the 3rd century BC, legionaries were paid a stipend.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] By the time of Augustus, the ideal of the citizen-soldier had been abandoned and the legions had become fully professional.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] At the end of the Civil War, Augustus reorganised Roman military forces, discharging soldiers and disbanding legions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] He retained 28 legions, distributed through the provinces of the Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the Principate, the tactical organisation of the Army continued to evolve.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The *auxilia* remained independent cohorts, and legionary troops often operated as groups of cohorts rather than as full legions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] A new and versatile type of unit, the *cohortes equitatae*, combined cavalry and legionaries in a single formation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] They could be stationed at garrisons or outposts and could fight on their own as balanced small forces or combine with similar units as a larger, legion-sized force.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] This increase in organizational flexibility helped ensure the long-term success of Roman military forces.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor Gallienus (253–268 AD) began a reorganisation that created the last military structure of the late Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Withdrawing some legionaries from the fixed bases on the border, Gallienus created mobile forces (the *comitatenses*, or field armies) and stationed them behind and at some distance from the borders as a strategic reserve.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The border troops (*limitanei*) stationed at fixed bases continued to be the first line of defence.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of the field army were regimental; *legiones* or *auxilia* for infantry and *vexillationes* for cavalry.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Nominal strengths may have been 1,200 men for infantry regiments and 600 for cavalry, but actual troop levels could have been much lower—800 infantry and 400 cavalry.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Many infantry and cavalry regiments operated in pairs under the command of a *comes*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Field armies included regiments recruited from allied tribes and known as *foederati*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] By 400 AD, *foederati* regiments had become permanently established units of the Roman army, paid and equipped by the Empire, led by a Roman tribune and used just as Roman units were used.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire also used groups of barbarians to fight along with the legions as allies without integration into the field armies, under overall command of a Roman general, but led by their own officers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Military leadership evolved over the course of the history of Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Under the monarchy, the hoplite armies were led by the kings.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the early and middle Roman Republic, military forces were under the command of one of the two elected consuls for the year.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the later Republic, members of the Roman Senatorial elite, as part of the normal sequence of elected public offices known as the *cursus honorum*, would have served first as *quaestor* (often posted as deputies to field commanders), then as *praetor*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Following the end of a term as praetor or consul, a Senator might be appointed by the Senate as a *propraetor* or *proconsul* (depending on the highest office held before) to govern a foreign province.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Under Augustus, whose most important political priority was to place the military under a permanent and unitary command, the Emperor was the legal commander of each legion but exercised that command through a *legatus* (legate) he appointed from the Senatorial elite.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the later stages of the Imperial period (beginning perhaps with Diocletian), the Augustan model was abandoned.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Provincial governors were stripped of military authority, and command of the armies in a group of provinces was given to generals (*duces*) appointed by the Emperor.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] These were no longer members of the Roman elite but men who came up through the ranks and had seen much practical soldiering.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] With increasing frequency, these men attempted (sometimes successfully) to usurp the positions of the Emperors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Decreased resources, increasing political chaos and civil war eventually left the Western Empire vulnerable to attack and takeover by neighbouring barbarian peoples.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Less is known about the Roman navy than the Roman army.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Prior to the middle of the 3rd century BC, officials known as *duumviri navales* commanded a fleet of twenty ships used mainly to control piracy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] This fleet was given up in 278 AD and replaced by allied forces.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The First Punic War required that Rome build large fleets, and it did so largely with the assistance of and financing from allies.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] This reliance on allies continued to the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The quinquereme was the main warship on both sides of the Punic Wars and remained the mainstay of Roman naval forces until replaced by the time of Caesar Augustus by lighter and more manoeuvrable vessels.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Ships were commanded by a *navarch*, a rank equal to a centurion, who was usually not a citizen.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Potter suggests that because the fleet was dominated by non-Romans, the navy was considered non-Roman and allowed to atrophy in times of peace.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Information suggests that by the time of the late Empire (350 AD), the Roman navy comprised several fleets including warships and merchant vessels for transportation and supply.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Warships were oared sailing galleys with three to five banks of oarsmen.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Fleet bases included such ports as Ravenna, Arles, Aquilea, Misenum and the mouth of the Somme River in the West and Alexandria and Rhodes in the East.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Flotillas of small river craft (*classes*) were part of the *limitanei* (border troops) during this period, based at fortified river harbours along the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] That prominent generals commanded both armies and fleets suggests that naval forces were treated as auxiliaries to the army and not as an independent service.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The details of command structure and fleet strengths during this period are not well known, although fleets were commanded by prefects.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome commanded a vast area of land, with tremendous natural and human resources.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] As such, Rome's economy remained focused on farming and trade.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Agricultural free trade changed the Italian landscape, and by the 1st century BC, vast grape and olive estates had supplanted the yeoman farmers, who were unable to match the imported grain price.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The annexation of Egypt, Sicily and Tunisia in North Africa provided a continuous supply of grains.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In turn, olive oil and wine were Italy's main exports.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Two-tier crop rotation was practised, but farm productivity was low.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Industrial and manufacturing activities were small.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The largest such activities were the mining and quarrying of stones, which provided basic construction materials for the buildings of that period.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In manufacturing, production was on a relatively small scale, and generally consisted of workshops and small factories that employed at most dozens of workers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, some brick factories employed hundreds of workers.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The economy of the early Republic was largely based on smallholding and paid labour.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, foreign wars and conquests made slaves increasingly cheap and plentiful, and by the late Republic, the economy was largely dependent on slave labour for both skilled and unskilled work.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Slaves are estimated to have constituted around 20% of the Roman Empire's population at this time and 40% in the city of Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Only in the Roman Empire, when the conquests stopped and the prices of slaves increased, did hired labour become more economical than slave ownership.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Although barter was used in ancient Rome, and often used in tax collection, Rome had a very developed coinage system, with brass, bronze, and precious metal coins in circulation throughout the Empire and beyond—some have even been discovered in India.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Before the 3rd century BC, copper was traded by weight, measured in unmarked lumps, across central Italy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The original copper coins (*as*) had a face value of one Roman pound of copper, but weighed less.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, Roman money's utility as a unit of exchange consistently exceeded its intrinsic value as metal.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] After Nero began debasing the silver denarius, its legal value was an estimated one-third greater than its intrinsic value.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Horses were expensive and other pack animals were slower.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Mass trade on the Roman roads connected military posts, where Roman markets were centered.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] As a result, there was transport of commodities between Roman regions, but increased with the rise of Roman maritime trade in the 2nd century BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During that period, a trading vessel took less than a month to complete a trip from Gades to Alexandria via Ostia, spanning the entire length of the Mediterranean.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Transport by sea was around 60 times cheaper than by land, so the volume for such trips was much larger.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Some economists consider the Roman Empire a market economy, similar in its degree of capitalistic practices to the 17th-century Netherlands and 18th-century England.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of Roman society were households and families.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Groups of households connected through the male line formed a family (*gens*), based on blood ties, a common ancestry or adoption.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the Republic, some powerful families, or *Gentes Maiores*, came to dominate political life.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Families were headed by their oldest male citizen, the *pater familias* (father of the family), who held lawful authority (*patria potestas*, 'father's power') over wives, sons, daughters, and slaves of the household, and the family's wealth.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The extreme expressions of this power—the selling or killing of family members for moral or civil offences, including simple disobedience—were very rarely exercised, and were forbidden in the Imperial era.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] A *pater familias* had moral and legal duties towards all family members.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Even the most despotic *pater familias* was expected to consult senior members of his household and *gens* over matters that affected the family's well-being and reputation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, such matters were regarded as outside the purview of the state and its magistrates; under the emperors, they were increasingly subject to state interference and legislation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Once accepted into their birth family by their fathers, children were potential heirs.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] They could not be lawfully given away, or sold into slavery.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] If parents were unable to care for their child, or if its paternity was in doubt, they could resort to infant exposure (Boswell translates this as being "offered" up to care by the gods or strangers).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] If a deformed or sickly newborn was patently "unfit to live", killing it was a duty of the *pater familias*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] A citizen father who exposed a healthy freeborn child was not punished, but automatically lost his *potestas* over that child.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Abandoned children were sometimes adopted; some would have been sold into slavery.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Slavery was near-ubiquitous and almost universally accepted.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, citizens in debt were allowed to sell their labour, and perhaps their sons, to their debtor in a limited form of slavery called *nexum* but this was abolished in the middle Republic.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Freedom was considered a natural and proper state for citizens; slaves could be lawfully freed, with consent and support of their owners, and still serve their owners' family and financial interests, as freedmen or freed women.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] This was the basis of the client-patron relationship, one of the most important features of Rome's economy and society.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In law, a *pater familias* held *potestas* over his adult sons with their own households.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] This could give rise to legal anomalies, such as adult sons also having the status of minors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] No man could be considered a *pater familias*, nor could he truly hold property under law, while his own father lived.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During Rome's early history, married daughters came under the control (*manus*) of their husbands' *pater familias*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] By the late Republic, most married women retained lawful connection to their birth family, though any children from the marriage belonged to her husband's family.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The mother or an elderly relative often raised both boys and girls.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman moralists held that marriage and child-raising fulfilled a basic duty to family, *gens*, and the state.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Fathers usually began seeking husbands for their daughters when these reached an age between twelve and fourteen, but most commoner-class women stayed single until their twenties, and in general seem to have been far more independent than wives of the elite.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Divorce required the consent of one party, along with the return of any dowry.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Both parents had power over their children during their minority and adulthood, but husbands had much less control over their wives.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman citizen women held a restricted form of citizenship; they could not vote but were protected by law.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] They ran families, could own and run businesses, own and cultivate land, write their own wills, and plead in court on their own behalf, or on behalf of others, all under dispensation of the courts and the nominal supervision of a senior male relative.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The latter was much resented, and the former had seemingly negligible results.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Aristocratic women seem to have been increasingly disinclined to childbearing.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman hours were counted ordinally from dawn to dawn.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, if sunrise was at 6 am, then 6 to 7 am was called the 'first hour'.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Midday was called *meridies*, and it is from this word that the terms *am* (*ante meridiem*) and *pm* (*post meridiem*) stem.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The English word "noon" comes from *nona* ('ninth (hour)'), which referred to 3 pm in ancient Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had clocks (*horologia*), which included giant public sundials (*solaria*) and water clocks (*clepsydrae*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman week originally had eight days, which were identified by letters A to H, with the eighth day being the *nundinum*, or market day, a kind of weekend when farmers sold their produce on the streets.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The seven-day week, introduced from the East during the early Empire, was officially adopted during the reign of Constantine.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Romans named week days after celestial bodies from at least the 1st century AD.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman year originally had ten months from Martius (March) to December, with the winter period not included in the calendar.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The first four months were named after gods (Martius, Aprilis, Maius, Junius) and the others were numbered (Quintilis, Sextilis, September, October, November, and December).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Numa Pompilius, the second king of Rome (716–673 BC), is said to have introduced the months of January and February, both also named after gods, beginning the 12-month calendar still in use today.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In 44 BC, the month Quintilis was renamed to Julius (July) after Julius Caesar and in 8 BC, Sextilis was renamed to Augustus (August) after Augustus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had several ways of tracking years.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] One widespread way was the consular dating, which identified years by the two consuls who ruled each year.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, introduced in the late 3rd century AD, was counting years from the *indictio*, a 15-year period based on the announcement of the delivery of food and other goods to the government.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, less popular but more similar to present day, was *ab urbe condita*, which counted years from the mythical foundation of Rome in 753 BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Life in ancient Rome revolved around the city of Rome, located on seven hills.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The city had a vast number of monumental structures like the Colosseum, the Trajan's Forum and the Pantheon.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] It had theatres, gymnasiums, marketplaces, functional sewers, bath complexes complete with libraries and shops, and fountains with fresh drinking water supplied by hundreds of miles of aqueducts.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the territory under the control of ancient Rome, residential architecture ranged from modest houses to country villas.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, there were imperial residences on Palatine Hill.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The low plebeian and middle equestrian classes lived in the city center, packed into apartments, or insulae, which were almost like modern ghettos.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] These areas, often built by upper class property owners to rent, were often centred upon collegia or taberna.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] These people, provided with a free supply of grain, and entertained by gladiatorial games, were enrolled as clients of patrons among the upper class patricians, whose assistance they sought and whose interests they upheld.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The native language of the Romans was Latin, an Italic language the grammar of which relies little on word order, conveying meaning through a system of affixes attached to word stems.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Its alphabet was based on the Etruscan alphabet, which was in turn based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Speakers of Latin could understand both until the 7th century when spoken Latin began to diverge so much that 'Classical' or 'Good Latin' had to be learned as a second language.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] While Latin remained the main written language of the Roman Empire, Greek came to be the language spoken by the well-educated elite, as most of the literature studied by Romans was written in Greek.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Most of the emperors were bilingual but had a preference for Latin in the public sphere for political reasons, a practice that first started during the Punic wars.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the eastern part of the Roman Empire (and later the Eastern Roman Empire), Latin was never able to replace Greek, a legacy of the Hellenistic period.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Justinian would be the last emperor to use Latin in government and marks when Greek officially took over.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The expansion of the Roman Empire spread Latin throughout Europe, and Vulgar Latin evolved into many distinct Romance languages.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Archaic Roman religion, at least concerning the gods, was made up not of written narratives, but rather of complex interrelations between gods and humans.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Unlike in Greek mythology, the gods were not personified, but were vaguely defined sacred spirits called *numina*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Romans also believed that every person, place or thing had its own *genius*, or divine soul.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the Roman Republic, Roman religion was organised under a strict system of priestly offices, which were held by men of senatorial rank.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The College of Pontifices was uppermost body in this hierarchy, and its chief priest, the *Pontifex Maximus*, was the head of the state religion.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Flamens took care of the cults of various gods, while augurs were trusted with taking the auspices.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The sacred king took on the religious responsibilities of the deposed kings.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman Empire, deceased emperors who had ruled well were deified by their successors and the Senate. and the formalised imperial cult became increasingly prominent.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] As contact with the Greeks increased, the old Roman gods became increasingly associated with Greek gods.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Under the Empire, the Romans absorbed the mythologies of their conquered subjects, often leading to situations in which the temples and priests of traditional Italian deities existed side by side with those of foreign gods.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning with Emperor Nero in the 1st century AD, Roman official policy towards Christianity was negative, and at some point, being a Christian could be punishable by death.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Under Emperor Diocletian, the persecution of Christians reached its peak.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, it became an officially supported religion in the Roman state under Diocletian's successor, Constantine I, with the signing of the Edict of Milan in 313, and quickly became dominant.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] All religions except Christianity were prohibited in 391 AD by an edict of Emperor Theodosius I.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Like many ancient cultures, concepts of ethics and morality, while sharing some commonalities with modern society, differed greatly in several important ways.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Because ancient civilisations like Rome were under constant threat of attack from marauding tribes, their culture was necessarily militaristic with martial skills being a prized attribute.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Whereas modern societies consider compassion a virtue, Roman society considered compassion a vice, a moral defect.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] One of the primary purposes of the gladiatorial games was to inoculate Roman citizens from this weakness.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Romans instead prized virtues such as courage and conviction (*virtus*), a sense of duty to one's people, moderation and avoiding excess (*moderatio*), forgiveness and understanding (*clementia*), fairness (*severitas*), and loyalty (*pietas*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society had well-established and restrictive norms related to sexuality, though as with many societies, the lion's share of the responsibilities fell on women.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Women were generally expected to be monogamous having only a single husband during their life (*univira*), though this was much less regarded by the elite, especially under the empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Women were expected to be modest in public avoiding any provocative appearance and to demonstrate absolute fidelity to their husbands (*pudicitia*).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Wearing a veil was a common expectation to preserve modesty.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Sex outside of marriage was generally frowned upon for men and women and was made illegal during the imperial period.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Nevertheless, prostitution was an accepted and regulated practice.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Public demonstrations of death, violence, and brutality were used as a source of entertainment in Roman communities; however it was also a way to maintain social order, demonstrate power, and signify communal unity.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman painting styles show Greek influences, and surviving examples are primarily frescoes used to adorn the walls and ceilings of country villas, though Roman literature includes mentions of paintings on wood, ivory, and other materials.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Several examples of Roman painting have been found at Pompeii, and from these art historians divide the history of Roman painting into four periods.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The first style of Roman painting was practised from the early 2nd century BC to the early- or mid-1st century BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] It was mainly composed of imitations of marble and masonry, though sometimes including depictions of mythological characters.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The second style began during the early 1st century BC and attempted to depict realistically three-dimensional architectural features and landscapes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The third style occurred during the reign of Augustus (27 BC – 14 AD), and rejected the realism of the second style in favour of simple ornamentation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] A small architectural scene, landscape, or abstract design was placed in the center with a monochrome background.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The fourth style, which began in the 1st century AD, depicted scenes from mythology, while retaining architectural details and abstract patterns.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Portrait sculpture used youthful and classical proportions, evolving later into a mixture of realism and idealism.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the Antonine and Severan periods, ornate hair and bearding, with deep cutting and drilling, became popular.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were also made in relief sculptures, usually depicting Roman victories.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman music was largely based on Greek music, and played an important part in many aspects of Roman life.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman military, musical instruments such as the *tuba* (a long trumpet) or the *cornu* were used to give various commands, while the *buccina* (possibly a trumpet or horn) and the *lituus* (probably an elongated J-shaped instrument), were used in ceremonial capacities.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Music was used in the Roman amphitheatres between fights and in the *odea*, and in these settings is known to have featured the *cornu* and the *hydraulis* (a type of water organ).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Most religious rituals featured musical performances.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Some music historians believe that music was used at almost all public ceremonies.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The graffiti, brothels, paintings, and sculptures found in Pompeii and Herculaneum suggest that the Romans had a sex-saturated culture.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Latin literature was, from its start, influenced heavily by Greek authors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Some of the earliest extant works are of historical epics telling the early military history of Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] As the Republic expanded, authors began to produce poetry, comedy, history, and tragedy.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome's literary contributions are still recognised today and the works by ancient Roman authors were available in bookshops as well as in public and private libraries.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Many scholars and statesmen of ancient Rome cultivated private libraries that were used both as demonstrations of knowledge and displays of wealth and power.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Although Julius Caesar had intended to establish public libraries to further establish Rome as a great cultural center like Athens and Alexandria, he died before this was accomplished.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Caesar's former lieutenant, Gaius Asinius Pollio, took up the project and opened the first public library in Rome in the Atrium Libertatis.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Emperors Augustus, Tiberius, Vespasian, Domitian, and Trajan also founded or expanded public libraries in Rome during their reigns.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] These included the Ulpian Library in Trajan's Forum and libraries in the Temple of Apollo Palatinus, the Temple of Peace in the Roman Forum, the Temple of Divus Augustus, which was dedicated to Minerva when it was rebuilt under Emperor Domitian's orders.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] By the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the city of Rome had more than two dozen public libraries.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] As the Roman Empire spread, public libraries were established in other major cities and cultural centers including Ephesos, Athens, and Timgad.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Roman cuisine changed over the long duration of this ancient civilisation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Dietary habits were affected by the influence of Greek culture, the political changes from Kingdom to Republic to Empire, and the Empire's enormous expansion, which exposed Romans to many new, provincial culinary habits and cooking techniques.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the beginning the differences between social classes were relatively small, but disparities evolved with the Empire's growth.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Men and women drank wine with their meals.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman diet included many items that are staples of modern Italian cooking.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] However, some foods now considered characteristic of modern Italian cuisine were not used.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In particular, spinach and eggplant (aubergine) were introduced later from the Arab world, and tomatoes, potatoes, capsicum peppers, and maize (the modern source of polenta) only appeared in Europe following the discovery of the New World and the Columbian Exchange.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans knew of rice, but it was very rarely available to them.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Butcher's meat such as beef was an uncommon luxury.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The most popular meat was pork, especially sausages.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Fish was more common than meat, with a sophisticated aquaculture and large-scale industries devoted to oyster farming.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also engaged in snail farming and oak grub farming.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Some fish were greatly esteemed and fetched high prices, such as mullet raised in the fishery at Cosa, and "elaborate means were invented to assure its freshness".
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, a breakfast called *ientaculum* was served at dawn.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] At mid-day to early afternoon, Romans ate *cena*, the main meal of the day, and at nightfall a light supper called *vesperna*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] With the increased importation of foreign foods, the *cena* grew larger in size and included a wider range of foods.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, it gradually shifted to the evening, while the *vesperna* was abandoned completely over the course of the years.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The mid-day meal *prandium* became a light meal to hold one over until *cena*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The toga, a common garment during the era of Julius Caesar, was gradually abandoned by all social classes of the Empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] At the early 4th century, the toga had become just a garment worn by senators in Senate and ceremonial events.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] At the 4th century, the toga was replaced by the *paenula* (a garment similar to a poncho) as the everyday garment of the Romans, from the lower classes to the upper classes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Another garment that was popular among the Romans in the later years of the Western Roman Empire was the *pallium*, which was mostly worn by philosophers and scholars in general.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Due to external influences, mainly from the Germanic peoples, the Romans adopted tunics very similar to those used by the Germanic peoples with whom they interacted in the final years of the Western Empire, also adopted trousers and hats like the *pileus pannonicus*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] During the Late Empire, the *paludamentum* (a type of military clothing) was used only by the Emperor of Rome (since the reign of Augustus, the first emperor) while the dalmatic (also used by the Christian clergy) began to spread throughout the empire.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The youth of Rome had several forms of athletic play and exercise.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Play for boys was supposed to prepare them for active military service, such as jumping, wrestling, boxing, and racing.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the countryside, pastimes for the wealthy also included fishing and hunting.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also had several forms of ball playing, including one resembling handball.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Dice games, board games, and gamble games were popular pastimes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] For the wealthy, dinner parties presented an opportunity for entertainment, sometimes featuring music, dancing, and poetry readings.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The majority, less well-off, sometimes enjoyed similar parties through clubs or associations, but for most Romans, recreational dining usually meant patronising taverns.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Children entertained themselves with toys and such games as leapfrog.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Public games and spectacles were sponsored by leading Romans who wished to advertise their generosity and court popular approval; in Rome or its provinces, this usually meant the emperor or his governors.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Venues in Rome and the provinces were developed specifically for public games.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Rome's Colosseum was built in 70 AD under the Roman emperor Vespasian and opened in 80 AD to host other events and gladiatorial combats.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Gladiators sometimes fought to the death, but more often to an adjudicated victory, usually in keeping with the mood of the watching crowd.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Shows of exotic animals were popular in their own right; but sometimes animals were pitted against human beings, either armed professionals or unarmed criminals who had been condemned to public death.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Chariot racing was extremely popular among all classes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, these races were usually held at the Circus Maximus, which had been purpose-built for chariot and horse-racing and, as Rome's largest public place, was also used for festivals and animal shows.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome boasted impressive technological feats, using many advancements that were lost in the Middle Ages and not rivalled again until the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] An example of this is insulated glazing, which was not invented again until the 1930s.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Many practical Roman innovations were adopted from earlier Greek designs.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were often divided and based on craft.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Artisans guarded technologies as trade secrets.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Roman civil engineering and military engineering constituted a large part of Rome's technological superiority and legacy, and contributed to the construction of hundreds of roads, bridges, aqueducts, public baths, theatres and arenas.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Many monuments, such as the Colosseum, Pont du Gard, and Pantheon, remain as testaments to Roman engineering and culture.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans were renowned for their architecture, which is grouped with Greek traditions into "Classical architecture".
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Although there were many differences from Greek architecture, Rome borrowed heavily from Greece in adhering to strict, formulaic building designs and proportions.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Aside from two new orders of columns, composite and Tuscan, and from the dome, which was derived from the Etruscan arch, Rome had relatively few architectural innovations until the end of the Republic.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] In the 1st century BC, Romans started to use Roman concrete widely.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Concrete was invented in the late 3rd century BC.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] It was a powerful cement derived from pozzolana, and soon supplanted marble as the chief Roman building material and allowed many daring architectural forms.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Also in the 1st century BC, Vitruvius wrote *De architectura*, possibly the first complete treatise on architecture in history.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also largely built using timber, causing a rapid decline of the woodlands surrounding Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] It is suggested that timber, around 4 metres (13 ft) long, came up to Rome via the Tiber River on ships travelling across the Mediterranean Sea from the confluence of the Saône and Rhône rivers in what is now the city of Lyon in present-day France.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] With solid foundations and good drainage, Roman roads were known for their durability and many segments of the Roman road system were still in use a thousand years after the fall of Rome.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The construction of a vast and efficient travel network throughout the Empire dramatically increased Rome's power and influence.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] They allowed Roman legions to be deployed rapidly, with predictable marching times between key points of the empire, no matter the season.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] These highways also had enormous economic significance, solidifying Rome's role as a trading crossroads—the origin of the saying "all roads lead to Rome".
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman government maintained a system of way stations, known as the *cursus publicus*, and established a system of horse relays allowing a dispatch to travel up to 80 km (50 mi) a day.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans constructed numerous aqueducts to supply water to cities and industrial sites and to aid in their agriculture.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] By the third century, the city of Rome was supplied by 11 aqueducts with a combined length of 450 km (280 mi).
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also made major advancements in sanitation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Romans were particularly famous for their public baths, called *thermae*, which were used for both hygienic and social purposes.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Many Roman houses had flush toilets and indoor plumbing, and a complex sewer system, the *Cloaca Maxima*, was used to drain the local marshes and carry waste into the Tiber.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have speculated that lead pipes in the sewer and plumbing systems led to widespread lead poisoning, which contributed to fall of Rome; however, lead content would have been minimised.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Ancient Rome is the progenitor of Western civilisation.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] The customs, religion, law, technology, architecture, political system, military, literature, languages, alphabet, government and many factors and aspects of western civilisation are all inherited from Roman advancements.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] The rediscovery of Roman culture revitalised Western civilisation, playing a role in the Renaissance and the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] The two longest ancient accounts of the Roman history, the histories of Livy and Dionysius of Halicarnassus, were composed 500 years later than the date for the founding of the republic and 200 years from the defeat of Hannibal.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Although there has been a diversity of works on ancient Roman history, many of them are lost.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] As a result of this loss, there are gaps in Roman history, which are filled by unreliable works, such as the **Historia Augusta**.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Caesar wrote his own accounts of his military campaigns in Gaul and during the Civil War in part to impress his contemporaries.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] In the Empire, the biographies of famous men and early emperors flourished, examples being *The Twelve Caesars* of Suetonius, and Plutarch's *Parallel Lives*.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Other major works of Imperial times were that of Livy and Tacitus.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Interest in studying, and idealising, ancient Rome became prevalent during the Italian Renaissance.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Edward Gibbon's *The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* "began the modern study of Roman history in the English-speaking world".
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] Barthold Georg Niebuhr was a founder of the examination of ancient Roman history and wrote *The Roman History*, tracing the period until the First Punic War.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] During the Napoleonic, *The History of Romans* by Victor Duruy highlighted the Caesarean period popular at the time.
[src:vidin/ancient-rome-p03] *History of Rome*, *Roman constitutional law* and *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*, all by Theodor Mommsen, became milestones.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] At birth, Anna was betrothed to Constantine Doukas, and she grew up in his mother's household.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She was well-educated in "Greek literature and history, philosophy, theology, mathematics, and medicine." Anna and Constantine were next in the line to throne until Anna's younger brother, John II Komnenos, became the heir in 1092.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Constantine died around 1094, and Anna married Nikephoros Bryennios in 1097.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] The two had several children before Nikephoros' death around 1136.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] It is commonly believed that, following her father's death in 1118, Anna and her mother attempted to usurp John II Komnenos.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Supposedly her husband refused to cooperate with them, and the usurpation failed.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] As a result, John exiled Anna to the Kecharitomene Monastery, where she spent the rest of her life, and in her confinement there she wrote the *Alexiad*.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] However, there is no contemporary evidence of Anna's involvement in any assassination attempt.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna was born on 1 December 1083 to Alexios I Komnenos and Irene Doukaina.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Her father, Alexios I Komnenos, became emperor in 1081, after usurping the previous Byzantine Emperor, Nikephoros Botaneiates.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Her mother, Irene Doukaina, was part of the imperial Doukas family.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In the *Alexiad*, Anna emphasises her affection for her parents in stating her relationship to Alexios and Irene.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She was the eldest of seven children; her younger siblings were (in order) Maria, John II, Andronikos, Isaac, Eudokia, and Theodora.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna was born in the Porphyra Chamber of the imperial palace in Constantinople, making her a *porphyrogenita,* which underscored her imperial status.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She noted this status in the *Alexiad,* stating that she was "born and bred in the purple." According to Anna's description in the *Alexiad*, her mother asked Anna to wait to be born until her father returned from war.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Obediently, Anna waited until her father came home.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] At birth, Anna was betrothed to Constantine Doukas, the son of Emperor Michael VII and Maria of Alania.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] The two were the heirs to the empire until sometime between c.1088 and 1092, after the birth of Anna's brother, John II Komnenos.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Various scholars point out that the betrothal was probably a political match intended to establish the legitimacy of Anna's father, who had usurped the previous emperor.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Starting around 1090, Constantine's mother – Maria of Alania – raised Anna in her home.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] It was common in Byzantium for mothers-in-law to raise daughters-in-law.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In 1094, Maria of Alania was implicated in an attempt to overthrow Alexios I Komnenos.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Some scholars argue that Anna's betrothal to Constantine Doukas may not have ended there, as he was not implicated in the plot against Alexios, but it certainly ended when he died around 1094.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna's relationships to her mother-in-law Maria of Alania, her paternal grandmother Anna Dalassene, and her mother Irene Doukaina, have been noted as sources of inspiration and admiration for Anna.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna wrote at the beginning of the *Alexiad* about her education, highlighting her experience with literature, Greek language, rhetoric, and sciences.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Tutors trained her in subjects that included astronomy, medicine, history, military affairs, geography, and mathematics.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] This testament is in contrast to a funeral oration about Anna given by her contemporary, Georgios Tornikes.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In his oration he said that she had to read ancient poetry, such as the *Odyssey*, in secret because her parents disapproved of its dealing with polytheism and other "dangerous exploits," which were considered "dangerous" for men and "excessively insidious" for women.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna proved to be capable not only on an intellectual level but also in practical matters.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She gained considerable expertise in medicine through studying medical texts and treating her family and members of her household, and she worked with her father's physicians to treat him during his final illness.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She was an expert on gout, and administered a huge hospital in Constantinople.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In roughly 1097, Anna's parents married her to *Caesar* Nikephoros Bryennios, a member of the Bryennios family that had held the throne before the accession of Anna's father, Alexios I.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Nikephoros was a soldier and a historian.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Most scholars agree that the marriage was a political one – it created legitimacy for Anna's paternal family through Bryennios' connections to past emperor's family.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] The two were an intellectual couple, and Nikephoros Bryennios tolerated and possibly encouraged Anna's scholarly interests by allowing her to participate in various scholarly circles.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] The couple had several children, of which many died in infancy.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Of them the names of six are known: Eirene, Maria, Alexios, John, Andronikos, and Constantine.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Only Eirene, Maria, John, and Alexios survived to adulthood.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In 1087, Anna's brother, John II, was born.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Several years after his birth, in 1092, John was designated emperor.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] According to Choniates, Emperor Alexios "favoured" John and declared him emperor while the Empress Irene "threw her full influence on [Anna's] side" and "continually attempted" to persuade the emperor to designate Nikephoros Bryennios, Anna's husband, in John's place.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Around 1112, Alexios fell sick with rheumatism and could not move.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] He therefore turned the civil government over to his wife, Irene; she in turn directed the administration to Bryennios.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Choniates states that, as Emperor Alexios lay dying in his imperial bedchamber, John arrived and "secretly" took the emperor's ring from his father during an embrace "as though in mourning." Anna also worked in her husband's favour during her father's illness.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] A cleric acclaimed John emperor in Hagia Sophia.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Jarratt et al. record that Anna was "almost certainly" involved in the murder plot against John at Alexios's funeral.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Indeed, Anna, according to Barbara Hill, attempted to create military forces to depose John.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] According to Choniates, Anna was "stimulated by ambition and revenge" to scheme for the murder of her brother.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Smythe states the plots "came to nothing." Jarratt et al., record that, a short time afterward, Anna and Bryennios "organized another conspiracy." However, according to Hill, Bryennios refused to overthrow John, making Anna unable to continue with her plans.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Hill, however, points out that Choniates, whom the above sources draw upon, wrote after 1204, and accordingly was "rather far removed" from "actual" events and that his "agenda" was to "look for the causes" of the toppling of Constantinople in 1204.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In contrast, Leonora Neville argues that Anna was probably not involved in the attempted usurpation.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna plays a minor role in most of the available medieval sources – only Choniates portrays her as a rebel.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Choniates' history is from around 1204, almost a hundred years after Alexios I's death.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Instead, most of the sources question whether John II Komnenos' behaviour at his father's deathbed was appropriate.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] According to the account by Choniates (written after the Fourth Crusade), plots were discovered and Anna forfeited her estates.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] After her husband's death, she entered the convent of Kecharitomene, which had been founded by her mother.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In the seclusion of the monastery, Anna dedicated her time to studying philosophy and history.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She held esteemed intellectual gatherings, including those dedicated to Aristotelian studies.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna's intellectual genius and breadth of knowledge is evident in her few works.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Among other things, she was conversant with philosophy, literature, grammar, theology, astronomy, and medicine.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] It can be assumed because of minor errors that she may have quoted Homer and the Bible from memory when writing her most celebrated work, the *Alexiad*.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna wrote the *Alexiad* in the mid-1140s or 1150s.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna cited her husband's unfinished work as the reason why she began the *Alexiad*.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Before his death in 1137, her husband, Nikephoros Bryennios the Younger, was working on a history, which was supposed to record the events before and during the reign of Alexios I.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] His death left the history unfinished after recording the events of the reign of Emperor Nikephoros Botaneiates.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Ruth Macrides argues that while Bryennios' writing may have been a source of inspiration for the *Alexiad*, it is incorrect to suggest that the *Alexiad* was Bryennios' work edited by Anna (as Howard-Johnston has argued on tenuous grounds).
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In a statement on how she gathered her sources for the *Alexiad*, Anna wrote, "My material ... has been gathered from insignificant writings, absolutely devoid of literary pretensions, and from old soldiers who were serving in the army at the time that my father seized the Roman sceptre ...
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] I based the truth of my history on them by examining their narratives and comparing them with what I had written, and what they told me with what I had often heard, from my father in particular and from my uncles ...
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] From all these materials the whole fabric of my history – my true history – has been woven".
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Beyond just eyewitness accounts from veterans or her male family members, scholars have also noted that Anna used the imperial archives, which allowed her access to official documents.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] In the *Alexiad*, Anna provided insight on political relations and wars between Alexios I and the West.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] She vividly described weaponry, tactics, and battles.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] It has been noted that she was writing about events that occurred when she was a child, so these are not eye-witness accounts.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Her neutrality is compromised by the fact that she was writing to praise her father and denigrate his successors.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Despite her unabashed partiality, her account of the First Crusade is of great value to history because it is the only Byzantine eyewitness account available.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Thus, the *Alexiad* allows the events of the First Crusade to be seen from the Byzantine elite's perspective.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] It conveys the alarm felt at the scale of the western European forces proceeding through the Empire, and the dangers they might have posed to the safety of Constantinople.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna referred to the crusaders as "Celts", reflecting old Greek terminology for western barbarians.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] The *Alexiad* was written in Attic Greek, and the literary style is fashioned after Thucydides, Polybius, and Xenophon.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Consequently, it exhibits a struggle for an Atticism characteristic of the period, whereby the resulting language is highly artificial.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Peter Frankopan argues that the lapses in some of the chronology of events can in part be attributed to errors in, or lack of, source material for those events.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Anna herself also addressed these lapses, explaining them as a result of memory loss and old age.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] But regardless of errors in chronology, her history meets the standards of her time.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Moreover, the *Alexiad* sheds light on Anna's emotional turmoil, including her grief over the deaths of her father, mother, and husband, among other things.
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] At the end of the *Alexiad*, Anna wrote "But living I died a thousand deaths ...
[src:vidin/anna-komnene] Yet I am more grief-stricken than Niobe: after my misfortunes, great and terrible as they are, I am still alive – to experience yet more ...
[src:vidin/antarctica] Antarctica is, on average, the coldest, driest, and windiest of the continents, and has the highest average elevation.
[src:vidin/antarctica] It is mainly a polar desert, with annual precipitation of over 200 mm (8 in) along the coast and far less inland.
[src:vidin/antarctica] About 70% of the world's freshwater reserves are frozen in Antarctica, which, if melted, would raise global sea levels by almost 60 metres (200 ft).
[src:vidin/antarctica] Antarctica holds the record for the lowest measured temperature on Earth, −89.2 °C (−128.6 °F).
[src:vidin/antarctica] The coastal regions can reach temperatures over 10 °C (50 °F) in the summer.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Native species of animals include mites, nematodes, penguins, seals and tardigrades.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Where vegetation occurs, it is mostly in the form of lichen or moss.
[src:vidin/antarctica] The ice shelves of Antarctica were probably first seen in 1820, during a Russian expedition led by Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen and Mikhail Lazarev.
[src:vidin/antarctica] The decades that followed saw further exploration by French, American, and British expeditions.
[src:vidin/antarctica] The first confirmed landing was by a Norwegian team in 1895.
[src:vidin/antarctica] In the early 20th century, there were a few expeditions into the interior of the continent.
[src:vidin/antarctica] British explorers Douglas Mawson, Edgeworth David, and Alistair Mackay were the first to reach the magnetic South Pole in 1909, and the geographic South Pole was first reached in 1911 by Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Antarctica is governed by about 30 countries, all of which are parties of the 1959 Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:vidin/antarctica] According to the terms of the treaty, military activity, mining, nuclear explosions, and nuclear waste disposal are all prohibited in Antarctica.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Tourism, fishing and research are the main human activities in and around Antarctica.
[src:vidin/antarctica] During the summer months, about 5,000 people reside at research stations, a figure that drops to around 1,000 in the winter.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Despite the continent's remoteness, human activity has a significant effect on it via pollution, ozone depletion, and climate change.
[src:vidin/antarctica] The name given to the continent originates from the word *antarctic*, which comes from Middle French *antartique* or *antarctique* ('opposite to the Arctic') and, in turn, the Latin *antarcticus* ('opposite to the north').
[src:vidin/antarctica] *Antarcticus* is derived from the Greek ἀντι- ('anti-') and ἀρκτικός (*arktikos*, 'of the Bear [Ursa Major], northern').
[src:vidin/antarctica] The Greek philosopher Aristotle wrote in *Meteorology* about an "Antarctic region" in c.
[src:vidin/antarctica] The Greek geographer Marinus of Tyre reportedly used the name in his world map from the second century AD, now lost.
[src:vidin/antarctica] European ideas regarding the existence of a *Terra Australis*—a vast continent in the far south of the globe to balance the northern lands of Europe, Asia, and North Africa—had existed as an intellectual concept since classical antiquity.
[src:vidin/antarctica] *Terra Australis* was therefore the name used to refer to all hypothetical landmasses proposed to be where Antarctica is now known to exist.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Assertion of the presence of such a land lasted until the European discovery of Australia.
[src:vidin/antarctica] During the early 19th century, explorer Matthew Flinders doubted the existence of a detached continent south of Australia (then called New Holland) and thus advocated for the "Terra Australis" name to be used for Australia instead.
[src:vidin/antarctica] In 1824, the colonial authorities in Sydney officially renamed the continent of New Holland to Australia, leaving the term "Terra Australis" unavailable as a reference to Antarctica.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Over the following decades, geographers used phrases such as "the Antarctic Continent".
[src:vidin/antarctica] They searched for a more poetic replacement, suggesting names such as *Ultima* and *Antipodea*.
[src:vidin/antarctica] *Antarctica* was adopted in the 1890s, with the first use of the name being attributed to the Scottish cartographer John George Bartholomew.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Positioned asymmetrically around the South Pole and largely south of the Antarctic Circle (one of the five major circles of latitude that mark maps of the world), Antarctica is surrounded by the Southern Ocean.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Rivers exist in Antarctica; the longest is the Onyx.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Antarctica covers more than 14.2 million km2 (5,500,000 sq mi), almost double the area of Australia, making it the fifth-largest continent, and comparable to the surface area of Pluto.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Its coastline is almost 18,000 km (11,200 mi) long: as of 1983, of the four coastal types, 44% of the coast is floating ice in the form of an ice shelf, 38% consists of ice walls that rest on rock, 13% is ice streams or the edge of glaciers, and the remaining 5% is exposed rock.
[src:vidin/antarctica] The lakes that lie at the base of the continental ice sheet occur mainly in the McMurdo Dry Valleys or various oases.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Lake Vostok, discovered beneath Russia's Vostok Station, is the largest subglacial lake globally and one of the largest lakes in the world.
[src:vidin/antarctica] It was once believed that the lake had been sealed off for millions of years, but scientists now estimate its water is replaced by the slow melting and freezing of ice caps every 13,000 years.
[src:vidin/antarctica] During the summer, the ice at the edges of the lakes can melt, and liquid moats temporarily form.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Antarctica has both saline and freshwater lakes.
[src:vidin/antarctica] Antarctica is divided into West Antarctica and East Antarctica by the Transantarctic Mountains, which stretch from Victoria Land to the Ross Sea.
